BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 66.24000000000001 600 Td (Chapter 6: Recording Your First Episode) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Write a simple outline with bullet points rather than a word-for-word script.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Speaking from notes sounds natural while reading a script sounds robotic.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Start with a brief introduction: who you are and what the show is about.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Record your intro episode explaining why you started and what listeners will gain.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Speak as if you are talking to one friend, not a large audience.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (It is normal to feel awkward at first. Everyone improves with practice.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (If you make a mistake, pause for three seconds then re-say the sentence.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (The pause makes it easy to find and remove mistakes during editing.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Aim for episodes between twenty and forty-five minutes when starting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Record in a consistent position and distance from the microphone each time.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Drink water before and during recording to keep your voice clear.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Your first episode will not be perfect and that is completely okay.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (6) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
