stream
BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 116.16 600 Td (Chapter 14: Interview Tips) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Research your guest thoroughly before the interview. Listen to their other appearances.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Prepare ten to fifteen questions but be flexible to follow interesting tangents.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Start with easy warm-up questions to make your guest comfortable.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Ask open-ended questions that begin with how, why, or tell me about.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Listen actively and ask follow-up questions based on their answers.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Avoid yes-or-no questions that kill conversation momentum.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Let your guest finish speaking. Do not interrupt even if you are excited.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Record a brief pre-interview chat to test audio levels and build rapport.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Send guests a few topics in advance but not the exact questions.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Keep the energy conversational rather than formal like a news interview.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Thank your guest genuinely and make it easy for them to share the episode.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Great interviews feel like fascinating conversations, not interrogations.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 211.2 30 Td (14) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
